{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647780"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:48:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:48:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18265"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18265"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.79,0.04,0,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10979"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74134"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10979"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59625"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7417"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25539"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74134"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe femoral triangle is bounded by the inguinal ligament superiorly, the sartorius muscle laterally and the adductor longus muscle medially. There are a number of structures that cross this triangle and one particular vein that pierces the overlying cribriform fascia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is this vein?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior tibial","Great saphenous","Popliteal","Posterior tibial","Small saphenous"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egreat saphenous vein\u003C/strong\u003E is the longest vein in the body and is a superficial vein that runs along the medial aspect of the leg and thigh. It drains into the femoral vein within the femoral triangle. To do so, it pierces the cribriform fascia, a part of the fascia lata, to enter the femoral vein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall saphenous vein\u003C/strong\u003E is another superficial vein, but it runs along the posterior aspect of the leg and drains into the popliteal vein, not the femoral vein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epopliteal vein\u003C/strong\u003E is a deep vein located in the popliteal fossa behind the knee and is not part of the femoral triangle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior tibial vein\u003C/strong\u003E is a deep vein that runs along the anterior compartment of the leg and is not involved in the femoral triangle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior tibial vein\u003C/strong\u003E is a deep vein that runs along the posterior compartment of the leg and also does not participate in the femoral triangle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The great saphenous vein is a superficial vein that drains into the femoral vein within the femoral triangle.","The great saphenous vein pierces the cribriform fascia to enter the femoral vein."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59625"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18265"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59625"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T21:26:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T21:31:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10979"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74134"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"me